"Is Eco a bank?"

It's one of the most common questions we get about Eco.

TLDR: Nope, Eco is NOT a bank—it's one simple balance that lets you spend, send, save, and make money at the same time. 

Keep reading to learn more about why Eco isn't a bank 👇

Banks have always gotten a bad reputation. 

It feels like they're working *against* you instead of *for* you.

But is it because they're evil? Not exactly. 

Their behavior results from a financial system that was never designed for the ways we use money today.

Banks need to take from you to survive. 

So how do banks make money?

Two ways: either by earning interest on your money, or by charging you fees.

Let's talk about interest first...

The longer your money sits in a bank, the more they make off YOUR money.

But hasn't the pandemic lowered the interest banks can make on their loans?

Yep. In fact, the profit banks make from your deposits (the "net interest margin") has been falling for a while.

So what's their solution? 

Fees, fees, and more fees. 

Banks aren't dumb. As net interest margins fall and people store less in their bank accounts, banks have started charging more fees. 

Think fees for overdraft, early account closure, foreign transaction, ATM, min balance..

Basically, you lose when you do anything with a bank. 

Not only are you earning 1/100th of the interest on your money, but you're paying (on avg.) $20/month in fees. 

That's $250/year! 

What's even more staggering? 

Americans pay $30+ BILLION in overdraft fees each year.

Banks win when you lose.

BUT...it doesn't have to be like that. 

We created Eco to give you more control over your money, to liberate you from fees, and to let you start earning 2.5% APY!

Why does it take so long for money to move? Why can we only send bank transfers on business days? And why do you only get paid twice a month? 

Because financial institutions use the same processes to move money that they did in the 1970s.

The Pony Express.

That's how money used to move.

Founded in 1860, it was a network of 186 stations about 10 miles apart that allowed letters + checks to be sprinted across the country.

The problem? 

Within the system, the banks never sent confirmations to each other. 

So nobody really knew the state of everyone's accounts at any given moment.

Today we don't rely on the Pony Express. 

But we rely on a system built on the same foundations, that operates the same way. 

And that's a huge problem.

Cryptocurrencies often get a bad rap for being "risky."

Many people hesitate when they hear the word "crypto"—they wonder if it's legit, or if it's ok to use 🤔

After all, isn't your money safer in a brick and mortar bank? 🔐

Nope.

At Eco, we use the power of stablecoins—cryptocurrency directly backed by the US dollar—to ensure that your money is secure and will never lose its value.

We’re not trying to convince you to invest dollars or other fiat currency in some new, volatile asset. 

No, we’d like to build products for you using existing currencies and migrate to this new system to make life faster, cheaper, and easier — to make your money work for you.
